Option A: Sidecar collector pattern
Technical walkthrough

OCI logging and monitoring sidecars repository demonstrates a sidecar-style observability pattern for OCI Container Instances.

The pattern is simple:

    your application container writes log lines to a file on a shared volume

    your application container or helper process writes metric records as newline-delimited JSON to another file on a shared volume

    the log forwarder sidecar reads the log file and ships those lines to OCI Logging

    the metrics forwarder sidecar reads the metric file and ships those records to OCI Monitoring

    both forwarders authenticate by using OCI resource principal authentication

The sample `generator` image in this repository is only a stand-in for a real application. In a real deployment, you replace the generator image with your own application image and keep one or both forwarder images as the observability sidecars.

This approach is useful when your application already writes logs to a local file, when you want a separate component to handle log shipping and metric publishing, when you want to avoid embedding OCI Logging or OCI Monitoring SDK logic in the application itself, and when you want the runtime identity of the container instance to authenticate to OCI services.

Forwarder responsibilities:

    the log forwarder tails a shared log file, follows rotated successors, spools pending log batches to disk, and sends them to OCI Logging

    the metrics forwarder tails a shared metrics file, parses newline-delimited JSON metric records, spools pending metric batches to disk, and sends them to OCI Monitoring through the telemetry ingestion endpoint

Prerequisites:

Before deploying this pattern, you need a small set of OCI resources in place. Together, these resources provide network connectivity for the container instance, an OCI Logging destination for forwarded log lines, IAM permissions so the sidecars can authenticate with resource principals, and a runtime location where the application and sidecars can run together.

If you are using the example repository, Terraform can provision the prerequisites for you and you can skip most of this section.

1. Network resources:

You need a VCN and a subnet for the OCI Container Instance.

Typical network prerequisites include a VCN for the deployment boundary, a subnet where the container instance VNIC will be attached, a route table that gives the subnet outbound connectivity, an internet gateway or another valid outbound path depending on your network design, and a security list or NSG that allows the traffic your application requires. These resources are needed because the container instance must be placed inside a subnet, the runtime often needs outbound access to pull container images and reach OCI APIs, and any application endpoint that you expose must be protected by appropriate inbound rules from approved source ranges. In this sample repository, Terraform creates the VCN, subnet, route table, internet gateway, and security list.

2. Logging resources:

You need an OCI Logging destination before the log forwarder can ship anything.

The required logging resources are a log group and a custom log inside that log group. These resources are needed because the log group acts as the parent container for the logging resource, while the custom log is the actual destination that receives application log lines. The log forwarder sends data to that custom log by using its OCID.

The custom log OCID is passed into the log forwarder as:

    OCI_LOG_OBJECT_ID

3. Monitoring resources:

You need a target compartment and namespace before the metrics forwarder can publish anything.

The required monitoring inputs are the compartment OCID where custom metrics will be written and the namespace under which the metrics will be emitted. You can also define a resource group if you want to organize related custom metrics more cleanly. The metrics forwarder sends metric batches to OCI Monitoring by using the telemetry ingestion endpoint for the region.

The default monitoring inputs are passed into the metrics forwarder as:

    OCI_MONITORING_COMPARTMENT_ID

    OCI_MONITORING_NAMESPACE

Optional monitoring inputs include:

    OCI_MONITORING_RESOURCE_GROUP

    OCI_MONITORING_INGESTION_ENDPOINT

IAM resources:

Both forwarders use OCI resource principal authentication. Because of that, they do not use a user API key or a mounted OCI config file.

You need a dynamic group that matches the target container instance, a policy that grants that dynamic group permission to push log content and publish custom metrics, and permission for the runtime to pull images from the registry you use. These resources are needed because the dynamic group defines which runtime resources are treated as principals and the policy defines what those principals are allowed to do. Without those permissions, the sidecars cannot authenticate to OCI Logging or OCI Monitoring and the runtime may not be able to pull the container images.

At a minimum, the policy should allow the matched dynamic group to:

    use log content in the target compartment or log group

    use metrics in the target compartment

    read container repositories or otherwise pull the required images

Provisioning options:

You can create these prerequisites in different ways, including Terraform, the OCI Console, the OCI CLI, or an internal platform or deployment pipeline. This repository already includes Terraform under `container_instance/` that provisions the VCN, subnet, route table, internet gateway, security list, log group, custom log, dynamic group, IAM policy, and container instance. If you use that Terraform, you mainly need to provide your image URLs and deployment-specific variable values.

Walkthrough steps:

    Ensure prerequisites. If you are trying this out using the example repository, you can largely ignore this step because Terraform can provision the required OCI resources for you.

    Prepare images.

    Prepare the application container image whose log file path and metric file path are configurable. You can use the generator image provided in the example if you are just trying this out. The generator image starts an HTTP server that can write log messages and metric records to the shared files, which is useful for end-to-end testing.

    Prepare or reuse the log forwarder container image.

    Prepare or reuse the metrics forwarder container image.

    Push these images to container registries accessible from the container instance.

    Launch the container instance.

    Launch a container instance with the application container, the log forwarder sidecar if logging is enabled, the metrics forwarder sidecar if metrics are enabled, and the required Empty Dir style shared volumes.

    Ensure that the following container environment variables are configured properly.

    Application container environment variables if you are using the example generator:

    LOG_FILE_PATH: path of the shared log file

    METRIC_FILE_PATH: path of the shared metrics file

    Log forwarder container environment variables:

    LOG_FILE_PATH: path of the shared log file

    OCI_LOG_OBJECT_ID: OCI custom log OCID

    Metrics forwarder container environment variables:

    METRIC_FILE_PATH: path of the shared metrics file

    OCI_MONITORING_NAMESPACE: default custom metrics namespace

    OCI_MONITORING_COMPARTMENT_ID: target compartment OCID for custom metrics

    Verify OCI Logging.

    If you are using the generator image provided in the example, post custom log messages using curl and the public IP of the container instance. The exact command is provided in the repository README.

    Verify that the custom log messages are available in the OCI Logging resource. This can be verified through the OCI Console.

    Verify OCI Monitoring.

    If you are using the generator image provided in the example, post custom metric messages using curl and the public IP of the container instance.

    Verify that the custom metrics are available in OCI Monitoring under the configured namespace and compartment. This can be verified through the OCI Console or Monitoring queries.

Operational notes:

    the log forwarder preserves batching, on-disk spool recovery, inode-aware file tracking, and optional logrotate integration

    the metrics forwarder preserves batching, on-disk spool recovery, inode-aware file tracking, parsing of newline-delimited JSON metric records, and optional logrotate integration

    both sidecars are now implemented as small Go binaries, which keeps the container images much lighter while preserving the current behavior
